# Git â€” Add New Project to GitHub (First-Time Setup)

Use this rule when the user asks to **add a new project to Git**, **create a GitHub repo**, or **push an existing folder** that is not yet a git repository (e.g. `F:\project_workspace\misc-project`, `E:\project_workspace\catholicatenews-in`).

**Related rules (ongoing commits after setup):**
- [git_local_push.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/git_local_push.mdc) â€” secret filter, unstaged/untracked staging, pull-first
- [git_commit_push_release_deploy.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/git_commit_push_release_deploy.mdc) â€” commit + push + release deploy for existing repos

---

## **Overview**

| Step | Action |
|------|--------|
| 1 | Verify `.gitignore` (secrets, `.env*`, keys, IDE caches) |
| 2 | `git init` â†’ `git add -A` â†’ secret scan â†’ initial commit |
| 3 | `gh auth login` (one-time if `gh auth status` fails) |
| 4 | `gh repo create <name> --public\|--private --source=. --push` |
| 5 | Fallback: `git remote add origin` + `git branch -M main` + `git push -u origin main` |

**Canonical org:** `giventadevelop` (e.g. `https://github.com/giventadevelop/strapi-editorial-template.git`).

**Default branch:** `main`.

---

## **Step 1 â€” Pre-flight checks**

```powershell
cd F:\project_workspace\<project-folder>
Test-Path .git          # should be False before init
Test-Path .gitignore    # create or copy from common_project_work if missing
```

**DO:**
- âś… Copy or merge `.gitignore` from [common_project_work](mdc:F:/project_workspace/common_project_work/.gitignore) or sibling repos when the new project has no ignore file.
- âś… Ensure `.gitignore` blocks: `.env*`, `*.pem`, `*.key`, `auth.json`, `.auth-state`, `credentials.json`, `service-account*.json`, `.idea/`, `node_modules/`, `**/screenshots/`, local MCP credential files.

**DON'T:**
- âťŚ Run `git add .` and commit without scanning staged paths for secrets.
- âťŚ Commit `.env.local`, production DB env files, or session tokens.

---

## **Step 2 â€” Initialize and first commit (secret-safe)**

PowerShell: run commands **one per line** (no `&&`).

```powershell
cd F:\project_workspace\<project-folder>
git init
git status --porcelain

git add -A
git restore --staged tsconfig.tsbuildinfo 2>$null
git restore --staged code_html_template/SQLS/corrected_event_media_inserts.ordered_PROD.sql 2>$null
git diff --cached --name-only | Select-String -Pattern `
  'prod\.env$|\.env\.local|\.env\.production|auth\.json|\.auth-state|secrets|\.pem$|\.key$|credentials|ordered_PROD\.sql|\.log$' `
  -CaseSensitive:$false | ForEach-Object { git restore --staged $_.Line.Trim() }

# Must return empty:
git diff --cached --name-only | Select-String -Pattern `
  'prod\.env$|\.env\.local|auth\.json|secrets|\.pem$|\.key$|credentials' -CaseSensitive:$false

git commit -m "Initial commit"
git branch -M main
```

**Content spot-check** for any new env-like or credential-shaped file before commit (see [git_local_push.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/git_local_push.mdc)).

---

## **Step 3 â€” GitHub CLI authentication (one-time)**

```powershell
gh auth status
```

If login fails or token is invalid:

```powershell
gh auth login
# Follow prompts: GitHub.com â†’ HTTPS â†’ Login with browser (or paste PAT)
```

User may see auth errors on first `gh repo create`; completing `gh auth login` then retrying push is normal.

---

## **Step 4 â€” Create remote repo and push**

Replace `<repo-name>` with the GitHub repository name (usually the folder name, e.g. `misc-project`, `catholicatenews-in`).

**Option A â€” Create + push in one step (preferred):**

```powershell
cd F:\project_workspace\<project-folder>
# Public:
gh repo create giventadevelop/<repo-name> --public --source=. --remote=origin --push

# Or private:
gh repo create giventadevelop/<repo-name> --private --source=. --remote=origin --push
```

**Option B â€” Auth error fallback (manual remote + push):**

```powershell
cd F:\project_workspace\<project-folder>
gh repo create giventadevelop/<repo-name> --private --description "Short description" --confirm
git remote add origin https://github.com/giventadevelop/<repo-name>.git
git branch -M main
$env:GIT_SSL_NO_VERIFY = 'true'
git push -u origin main
Remove-Item Env:GIT_SSL_NO_VERIFY -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
```

**If remote already exists** (re-run setup):

```powershell
git remote -v
git remote set-url origin https://github.com/giventadevelop/<repo-name>.git
git push -u origin main
```

